## Selenium Interview Q&A (Python-ready)

1. What is Selenium?  
Open-source tool to automate web applications; controls browsers using Python, Java, C#; used for UI automation; integrates with CI/CD pipelines.

2. What is Selenium mainly used for?  
Automates web app testing (functional & regression), cross-browser testing, repetitive tasks; e.g., login, form submissions.

3. Important facts about Selenium  
Open-source, supports major browsers, multiple languages (Python, Java, C#), components: WebDriver, IDE, Grid; cross-platform, CI/CD ready.

4. Main components of Selenium  
WebDriver: browser automation  
IDE: record & playback  
Grid: parallel execution

5. What is Selenium WebDriver?  
Core component; simulates real-user actions; communicates directly with browser; fast & modern; widely used in Python projects.

6. What is Selenium IDE?  
Browser extension; records actions & auto-generates scripts; exports to Python, Java, C#, Ruby; less flexible than WebDriver; beginner-friendly.

7. What is Selenium Grid?  
Runs tests in parallel across multiple machines, browsers, OS; Hub/Node architecture; speeds up large test suites.

8. What is Selenium RC?  
Remote Control, older tool replaced by WebDriver; required server; slower & complex setup.

9. How is WebDriver different from RC?  
WebDriver communicates directly; RC needed a server; WebDriver is faster, simpler, and supports modern apps.

10. Can Selenium be used for mobile testing?  
Selenium handles only web automation; use Appium for Android/iOS mobile web apps (Appium uses WebDriver API).

11. Advantages of Selenium  
Open-source, multi-browser/language support, cross-platform, CI/CD integration, parallel execution, automates repetitive tasks, improves accuracy.

12. Limitations of Selenium  
Cross-browser issues, slower for large apps, dynamic element challenges, limited mobile support, no desktop app automation, no built-in reporting, high maintenance.

13. Handling dynamic elements  
Use Implicit/Explicit/Fluent Waits; robust locators (ID, XPath, CSS); handle AJAX; ensure element readiness.

14. Managing cross-browser issues  
Test on multiple browsers; use standard locators; avoid browser-specific assumptions; combine with Grid or cloud tools.

15. CI/CD integration  
Works with Jenkins, GitLab, Azure DevOps; runs automated tests on code push; provides faster feedback and bug detection.

16. Choosing IDE vs WebDriver  
IDE: beginners, prototypes; WebDriver: real projects, precise control, complex scenarios.

17. Why pick WebDriver over Grid?  
WebDriver: script creation & execution; Grid: scaling tests in parallel across browsers/machines.

18. Advanced user interactions in WebDriver  
Use ActionChains: drag & drop, mouse hover, keyboard actions, file upload; simulates real user behavior.

19. Selenium WebDriver workflow  
Script → Driver → Browser → Result; write Python/Java script, driver executes, browser performs actions, returns results.

20. Features of Selenium  
Multi-language & browser support, cross-platform, parallel execution, pop-ups/alerts handling, record/playback, lightweight, cloud testing support.

21. Real-world uses  
Regression testing, data scraping, automating repetitive tasks, CI/CD testing, cross-browser testing.

22. How to install Selenium for Python  
pip install selenium (Python must be installed and PATH set).

23. How to set up WebDriver in Python  
from selenium import webdriver  
driver = webdriver.Chrome()  
driver.get("https://www.google.com")  
driver.quit()

24. How to verify Selenium installation is working  
Run a sample script that opens a browser, navigates to a site, prints title, and quits; successful execution → installed.

25. Which browsers can you automate in Selenium Python?  
Chrome, Firefox, Edge (Selenium Manager handles drivers).

26. What is the get() method in Selenium WebDriver?  
Opens a website; driver.get("https://www.example.com").

27. Why is the get() method important?  
Browser opens but site does not load without it; first step in most scripts.

28. Python example using get()  
from selenium import webdriver  
driver = webdriver.Firefox()  
driver.get("https://www.google.com")  
driver.quit()

29. How do you locate elements in Selenium WebDriver?  
Using locators: ID, NAME, CLASS_NAME, TAG_NAME, LINK_TEXT, PARTIAL_LINK_TEXT, CSS SELECTOR, XPATH.

30. How do you interact with elements in Selenium WebDriver?  
.send_keys("text"), .clear(), .click(), keyboard keys with send_keys(Keys.KEY_NAME).

31. How do you handle iframes in Selenium?  
driver.switch_to.frame(iframe_element) → interact → driver.switch_to.default_content().

32. How do you locate multiple elements in Selenium WebDriver?  
driver.find_elements(By.TAG_NAME, "a") → returns list of elements.

33. Locator strategies for multiple elements  
By.NAME, By.XPATH, By.LINK_TEXT, By.PARTIAL_LINK_TEXT, By.TAG_NAME, By.CLASS_NAME, By.CSS_SELECTOR.

34. What happens if no elements are found with find_elements()?  
Returns empty list []; does not raise exception.

35. Python example for multiple elements  
from selenium import webdriver  
from selenium.webdriver.common.by import By  
driver = webdriver.Chrome()  
driver.get("https://example.com")  
elements = driver.find_elements(By.TAG_NAME, "a")  
for element in elements:  
    print(element.text)  
driver.quit()

36. When should you use find_elements()?  
Validate list items, tables, dropdowns, multiple similar buttons, extract data.

37. Best locator strategy in Selenium  
Priority: ID → NAME → CSS_SELECTOR → XPATH → CLASS_NAME → TAG_NAME → LINK_TEXT.

38. Why waits are needed in Selenium  
Modern web apps load dynamically; prevents NoSuchElementException & ElementNotVisibleException.

39. Types of waits in Selenium  
Implicit Wait (global), Explicit Wait (specific element), Fluent Wait (custom polling).

40. What is Explicit Wait?  
Waits until a specific condition occurs; faster than time.sleep().

41. How Explicit Wait works  
from selenium.webdriver.support.ui import WebDriverWait  
from selenium.webdriver.support import expected_conditions as EC  
from selenium.webdriver.common.by import By  
element = WebDriverWait(driver, 10).until(EC.presence_of_element_located((By.ID, "username")))

42. Common Expected Conditions  
title_is, title_contains, presence_of_element_located, visibility_of_element_located, element_to_be_clickable, alert_is_present.

43. Explicit Wait vs time.sleep()  
Explicit: waits only until condition met, faster, recommended.  
time.sleep(): waits fixed time, slower, not recommended.

44. Advantages of Explicit Wait  
Handles dynamic elements, reduces flaky tests, prevents unnecessary delays.

45. What is Implicit Wait?  
Maximum wait for element search; applied globally.

46. Characteristics of Implicit Wait  
Global, set once per session, simple, good for minor delays.

47. How Implicit Wait works internally  
Selenium polls repeatedly until timeout; continues immediately if element appears.

48. Advantages of Implicit Wait  
Simple, global, reduces NoSuchElementException for small delays.

49. Limitations of Implicit Wait  
Applies to all elements, less control, cannot wait for specific conditions.

50. What are Action Chains in Selenium?  
Advanced interactions: mouse hover, right click, drag & drop, keyboard shortcuts.

51. Why use Action Chains?  
Normal .click() or .send_keys() cannot handle complex actions.

52. How Action Chains work  
Create ActionChains(driver) → queue actions → .perform() to execute.

53. Common ActionChains methods  
click(), double_click(), context_click(), click_and_hold(), release(), move_to_element(), move_by_offset(x,y), drag_and_drop(source,target), send_keys(), key_down(), key_up(), pause(), perform().

54. Python example – Click an element  
actions = ActionChains(driver)  
actions.click(element).perform()

55. Python example – Mouse Hover  
actions = ActionChains(driver)  
actions.move_to_element(menu).perform()

56. Python example – Drag and Drop  
actions.drag_and_drop(source, target).perform()

57. Two ways to use ActionChains  
Chain pattern (single line) or queue pattern (multiple lines with .perform()).

58. What is an Alert in Selenium?  
Popup message outside DOM: information, confirmation, input.

59. How to handle Alerts in Selenium?  
Use Alert(driver) → .accept(), .dismiss(), .send_keys(), .text.

60. Common Alert methods  
accept(), dismiss(), send_keys("input"), text.

61. Steps to handle an Alert  
Trigger alert → alert = Alert(driver) → perform action (accept(), dismiss(), send_keys()).

62. Python example – Accept Alert  
alert = Alert(driver)  
alert.accept()

63. Python example – Dismiss Alert  
alert.dismiss()

64. Python example – Send Input to Alert  
alert.send_keys("Hello!")  
alert.accept()

65. Types of Alerts  
Simple (OK), Confirmation (OK/Cancel), Prompt (Input + OK/Cancel).

66. What are Cookies in Selenium?  
Data stored in browser: sessions, preferences, auth.

67. Cookie methods in Selenium WebDriver  
add_cookie(), get_cookie(), get_cookies(), delete_cookie().

68. Example workflow – Cookie Handling  
driver.add_cookie({"name":"foo","value":"bar"})  
cookie = driver.get_cookie("foo")  
driver.delete_cookie("foo")

69. What are Exceptions in Selenium?  
Errors during execution: element not found, hidden, unclickable, timeout, alert/frame missing.

70. Why Exceptions Occur  
Wrong locator, element not loaded, hidden/disabled, overlay, slow page load.

71. Common Selenium Exceptions  
NoSuchElementException, ElementClickInterceptedException, ElementNotInteractableException, NoAlertPresentException, NoSuchFrameException, TimeoutException, StaleElementReferenceException, InvalidSelectorException.

72. Python example – Handling Exceptions  
try:  
    element.click()  
except NoSuchElementException:  
    print("Element not found")

73. Why Exception Handling is Important  
Prevents test failures; ensures stable, reliable automation scripts.

74. What is an Assertion in Selenium?  
Validates expected vs actual result; passes or fails test.

75. Why Assertions Are Important  
Validation, bug detection, test reliability.

76. How Assertions Are Used in Selenium Python  
Built-in assert; frameworks: unittest, pytest.

77. Basic Python Assertion  
assert 5 > 3

78. Assertion with Custom Message  
assert driver.title == "Google", "Title does not match"

79. Common Assertions in Selenium Python  
Page title, element text, displayed status, URL, element existence.

80. Python example Selenium script with Assertion  
assert driver.title == "Google"

81. Assertions using unittest Framework  
self.assertEqual(driver.title, "Google")

82. Common unittest Assertions  
assertEqual, assertNotEqual, assertTrue, assertFalse, assertIsNone, assertIsNotNone

83. Real Selenium Test Example – Login Page  
assert driver.title == "Login Page"

84. What is Page Object Model (POM)?  
Design pattern: separate class per page with locators & actions; clean, reusable, maintainable.

85. Why Use POM?  
Easier maintenance; update locator once; reduces code duplication; better readability.

86. Advantages of POM  
Maintenance, reusability, readability, reduced duplication.

87. What is the difference between driver.close() and driver.quit()?  
- driver.close() → closes the current browser tab/window.  
- driver.quit() → closes all browser windows and ends the WebDriver session.

88. What is the difference between find_element and find_elements?  
- find_element → returns a single element, raises exception if not found.  
- find_elements → returns a list of elements, empty list if none found.

89. How do you handle StaleElementReferenceException?  
- Occurs when DOM updates after locating an element.  
Solutions: Re-find the element before interaction; use Explicit Waits until element is refreshed.

90. What is the difference between Absolute XPath and Relative XPath?  
- Absolute XPath → /html/body/div[1]/input → starts from root, brittle.  
- Relative XPath → //input[@id='username'] → starts anywhere in DOM, recommended.

91. What is Shadow DOM and how to handle it in Selenium?  
- Shadow DOM: hidden DOM attached to elements (Web Components).  
- Access using JavaScript:  
shadow_root = driver.execute_script('return arguments[0].shadowRoot', element)  
shadow_element = shadow_root.find_element(By.CSS_SELECTOR, 'button')

92. How do you take a screenshot in Selenium?  
- driver.save_screenshot("screenshot.png")  
- driver.get_screenshot_as_file("screenshot.png")

93. How do you scroll a page using Selenium?  
- driver.execute_script("window.scrollTo(0, document.body.scrollHeight)") → scroll bottom  
- driver.execute_script("arguments[0].scrollIntoView();", element) → scroll to element

94. How do you handle multiple windows or tabs in Selenium?  
- handles = driver.window_handles  
- driver.switch_to.window(handles[1])  # switch to second window/tab

95. How do you handle file uploads in Selenium?  
- element.send_keys("C:/path/to/file.txt")  # send file path to input type="file"

96. What is Fluent Wait in Selenium?  
- Wait with timeout + polling interval + ignored exceptions:  
from selenium.webdriver.support.ui import WebDriverWait  
from selenium.webdriver.support import expected_conditions as EC  
from selenium.common.exceptions import NoSuchElementException  

wait = WebDriverWait(driver, 10, poll_frequency=2, ignored_exceptions=[NoSuchElementException])  
element = wait.until(EC.element_to_be_clickable((By.ID, 'submit')))

97. How do you handle stale dropdowns or select elements?  
from selenium.webdriver.support.ui import Select  
select = Select(driver.find_element(By.ID, "dropdown"))  
select.select_by_visible_text("Option1")  
select.select_by_index(1)  
select.select_by_value("value1")

98. Difference between CSS Selector and XPath  
- CSS → faster, simpler for simple hierarchies  
- XPath → powerful, can traverse up/down, use functions, slightly slower

99. How to perform drag-and-drop using JavaScript when ActionChains fails?  
driver.execute_script("arguments[0].dispatchEvent(new DragEvent('dragstart'));", source)  
driver.execute_script("arguments[0].dispatchEvent(new DragEvent('drop'));", target)

100. How to wait for page to load completely?  
driver.execute_script("return document.readyState")  # returns "complete" when fully loaded

101. How to handle hidden elements in Selenium?  
- Use element.is_displayed() before interacting  
- Or JavaScript click: driver.execute_script("arguments[0].click();", element)

